column8: The client had asked for an expedited review, which is why the team had submitted layout and french in parallel. Andrei was reviewing only English copy (which we understand is traditionally the policy in a review process), but given the time sensitivity of the project we had hoped for more consolidated feedback on both French and layout to be able to address PAAB comments in parallel. The need to review the collateral was flagged in a number of rounds. During our calls with Andrei he was very helpful and offered a number of solutions to move the eFile around.
column10: Andrei was clear in his communication and what he needed to be revised in order to gain approval of the eFile. The core issue would be the inability to review English, French and layout at the same time (this was a client request). The resolution of the headline was appreciated as Andrei did a thorough job providing solutions, consulting internally and assessing our responses/precedence.
column12: This eFile for such a short APS went 7 rounds before receiving approval. We note that the feedback provided made sense but the concern for the client was time and as such the request for review in parallel (English, French and layout) was important for the finalization of the APS. The client felt that their request wasn't considered. Besides that a lot of the rounds were based on unsolicited changes and comments on layout/French.
column14: Overall the review with Andrei was fair and he's always been solution-oriented and pleasure to work with. The request to complete the CEI came from the client that felt that a parallel review should have been considered given the time sensitivity of the brand. We acknowledge theres a disconnect between the scale and the written feedback - we're sorry.

column8:
One major challenge in this review was whether the CanVasc guidelines were reflective of Canadian practice. Part of why this review took so long (9 PAAB rounds and multiple calls over 7 months) is that this challenge did not become clear to us until round 3 and after having a clarification call with the reviewer. 
At this point, the reviewer had already made comments on the guidelines presentation in the APS, without questioning whether they could be included (for example, in letter 2 point 7.) The problem with the use of the guideline only came up after the reviewer said we could not use CanVasc as a source of prevalence data. 
Throughout the review (both in writing and during the numerous clarification calls), it was very difficult to understand the underlying reasons for the reviewer's comment, which made addressing those comments challenging.
column10: In response letter 6, the reviewer had no further comments on the english copy. However, once the layout and the French were submitted, there were 2 more rounds of feedback regarding content of the copy.
column12: This review was extremely challenging from start to finish. It was difficult to understand the underlying reasons for a lot of the feedback. However, we are satisfied with the outcome of this review and we appreciate the time and attention of the senior reviewers.
